The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                       7                                                                                                        
	Lahore: The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) has threatened legal action against former South African coach Mickey Arthur, who had said that they suspected Pakistans involvement in match-fixing in 2007. PCB has decided to immediately serve a legal notice on Micky Arthur asking him to share with PCB any evidence in this regard, PCB said in a statement.        
	London: The probe into the spot-fixing allegations gathered pace on Friday as a second evidence file was passed to prosecutors. Scotland Yard said evidence that there was a conspiracy to defraud bookmakers will be considered by the Crown Prosecution Service (CPS).  
	Murali stand  
	Melbourne: Muttiah Muralidharan Friday said Australia do not have enough fire in their bowling unit, which is the reason for their extended poor run and may also dent chances in the upcoming Ashes series against England. At the moment, Australia are a bit down because of lack of talent, Murali told an Australian newspaper.  
	WICB diktat  
	St Johns: The West Indies Cricket Board (WICB), acting on BCCIs advice, has asked its cricketers who wish to play in the next three seasons of the IPL to approach the league through them and not through agents or directly. The cricketers have been asked to submit their expressions of interest to the WICB by November 9.   
	Somdev sails   
	Charlottesville: Somdev Dev Varman sailed into the singles quarter finals, while teen Yuki Bhambri crashed out of the ATP Challenger event in Charlottesville here.  
	Mahesh-Max up  
	Valencia: Mahesh Bhupathi and Max Mirnyi advanced to the semi-finals, while Rohan Bopanna and Aisam-ul-haq Qureshi sealed a quarter final berth in the Valencia Open.  
	Rafa withdraws  
	Paris: Top-ranked Rafael Nadal of Spain has withdrawn from the Paris Masters for medical reasons. Tournament director Jean-Francois Caujolle said Friday at the draw that he did not know the exact nature of Nadals ailment. The Spanish player recently said he was feeling some fatigue from a successful season.  
	Nicky in talks  
	Hong Kong: Hong Kong club South China say they are in talks with former Manchester United and Newcastle midfielder Nicky Butt. The club say that the 35-year old Englishman has agreed to train with the team in Hong Kong later this month and will make a decision during his stay.  
	Robbery  
	Marseille: The house of Marseille players Andre and Jordan Ayew has been robbed while they where away for a Champions League match in Slovakia. Police launched an investigation and said the robbers damaged the brothers villa in Marseille after breaking into the house by smashing a glass door.
                                                                                                                                                      
